                        <div class="gridColumn twelve breadcrumbs"><ul><li><a href="/">Home</a></li><li>/</li><li><a href="/news">News</a></li><li>/</li><li class="current">Ground-based detection of super-Earth transit paves way to remote sensing of small exoplanets</li></ul><div style="clear:both"></div></div>
                        <div class="article"><div class="addthis_sharing_toolbox shareIcons"></div><h1 class="headline">Ground-based detection of super-Earth transit paves way to remote sensing of small exoplanets</h1><div class="subheading">The transit of exoplanet 55 Cancri e is the shallowest detected from the ground yet.</div><div class="byline">
            By 
            <a href="/authors/york-university-toronto-ontario-canada">York University, Toronto, Ontario, Canada</a> Â |Â  
            Published: Tuesday, December 02, 2014</div><div class="tags">
          RELATED TOPICS: 
          <a href="/tags/exoplanets">EXOPLANETS</a> | <a href="/tags/stars">STARS</a></div><div style="margin:25px 0 0 0"><div class="segment" style=""><div class="heroTop"><div class="mediaContainer"><div><a href="/sitefiles/resources/image.aspx?item={37273D50-287C-41AA-8727-F2BFBC976CA0}" rev="colorbox"><img src="/-/media/Images/News and Observing/News/2014/12/Earth_and_Superearth.jpg?mw=600" alt="Earth and Superearth" width="600" height="360" /></a></div><div class="caption">Earth and super-Earth</div><div class="credit">NASA/JPL</div></div></div><div class="content">For the first time, a team of astronomers, including Ray Jayawardhana from York University, has measured the passing of a super-Earth in front of a bright nearby Sun-like star using a ground-based telescope. The transit of exoplanet 55 Cancri e is the shallowest detected from the ground yet, and the success bodes well for characterizing the many small planets that upcoming space missions are expected to discover in the next few years.<br />
<br />
The international research team used the 2.5-meter Nordic Optical Telescope on the island of La Palma, Spain, to make the detection. Previous observations of this planet transit had to rely on space-borne telescopes.<br />
<br />
During its transit, the planet crosses its host star, 55 Cancri, located just 40 light-years away from us and visible to the naked eye, blocking a tiny fraction of the starlight, dimming the star by 0.05% for almost two hours.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Our observations show that we can detect the transits of small planets around Sun-like stars using ground-based telescopes,&rdquo; said Ernst de Mooij from Queen&rsquo;s University Belfast in the United Kingdom. &ldquo;This is especially important because upcoming space missions such as TESS and PLATO should find many small planets around bright stars.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
TESS is a NASA mission scheduled for launch in 2017, while PLATO is to be launched in 2024 by the European Space Agency; both will search for transiting terrestrial planets around nearby bright stars.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s remarkable what we can do by pushing the limits of existing telescopes and instruments, despite the complications posed by the Earth&rsquo;s own turbulent atmosphere,&rdquo; said Jayawardhana. &ldquo;Observations like these are paving the way as we strive towards searching for signs of life on alien planets from afar. Remote sensing across tens of light-years isn&rsquo;t easy, but it can be done with the right technique and a bit of ingenuity.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The planet 55 Cancri e is about twice as big and eight times as massive as Earth. With a period of 18 hours, it is the innermost of five planets in the system. Because of its proximity to the host star, the planet&rsquo;s dayside temperature reaches over 3,100&deg; F (1,700&deg; C) &mdash; hot enough to melt metal &mdash; with conditions quite inhospitable to life. Initially identified a decade ago through radial velocity measurements, it was later confirmed through transit observations with the MOST and Spitzer space telescopes.<br />
<br />
Until now, the transits of only one other super-Earth, GJ 1214b circling a red dwarf, had been observed with ground-based telescopes. Earth&rsquo;s roiling air makes such observations extremely difficult. But the team&rsquo;s success with 55 Cancri e raises the prospects of characterizing dozens of super-Earths likely to be revealed by upcoming surveys.<br />
<br />
Next, the team plans to search for steam &mdash; water &mdash; in the planet&rsquo;s atmosphere.<br /></div><div style="clear:both;"></div></div></div><div class="commentcounts"><div class="bubble ptSans">0</div><div class="data"><h4 class="ptSans">JOIN THE DISCUSSION</h4>
          Read and share your comments on this article
